"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516583","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-11","<p>Statistics on the number of social dwellings sold by local authorities and private registered providers can be found in Live Table 678, which is too large to be included here but has been attached and can also be found here: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-social-housing-sales</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-05-11T15:20:45.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516583/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516583/answer","160503 Live table 678 - HL8095.xlsx","160503 Live table 678 - HL8095.xlsx","Table 678","Table 678","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516583/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-28","Social Rented Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many publicly owned or charity owned houses have been sold to their tenants in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL8095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516584","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-11","<p>One Highways England scheme has provided bat crossings as part of its construction during the last five years, and that is the A11 Fiveways to Thetford improvement scheme. Six crossings have been completed at a cost of £354,000.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-05-11T11:24:14.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516584/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516584/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516584/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-28","Bats","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many bat bridges over roads (1) have been completed in each of the last five years, (2) are under construction, and (3) are planned; and what is the (a) location, and (b) actual or budgeted cost of each.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL8096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516585","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-06","<p>All elements of road schemes are subject to appraisal in line with Treasury requirements and guidance. They are also subject to value management requirements throughout the project lifecycle.</p><p> </p><p>This does not include any specific measures on the cost-effectiveness of structures, such as bat bridges, as there is no accepted method for such quantatative evaluation. Instead a review is undertaken of the costs, qualitative benefits and other predicted impacts (including environmental) at key stages to ensure benefits are optimised and costs are challenged.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-05-06T08:41:49.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516585/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516585/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516585/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-28","Bats","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what measures are used (1) to determine the cost-effectiveness of bat bridges before construction is undertaken, and (2) to determine the value of those constructed.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL8097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516586","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-06","<p>Under the Environmental Protection Act 1990 (EPA), Highways England is responsible for litter clearance on all England’s motorways and a few selected A roads for specific operational reasons. Local authorities are responsible for litter on all local roads, including the vast majority A roads on the strategic road network.</p><p> </p><p>The M25 junction with the A12 trunk road (junction 28), is maintained by both Highways England and Transport for London. Transport for London is responsible for litter clearance of the A12 from junction 28 towards London and Brentwood Borough Council is responsible for Junction 28 towards Brentwood.</p><p> </p><p>A litter inspection of junction 28 was completed by Highways England on 21 April 2016 which identified ‘widespread distributions of litter with minor accumulations’ (Grade C under the EPA Code of Practice). This location was then cleared of litter on 26 April. The junction will continue to be regularly monitored and re-picked as the need arises.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-05-06T08:41:10.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516586/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516586/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-28","M25: A12","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment the Highways Agency has made of the standard of cleanliness of the junction between the M25 motorway and the A12 trunk road.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL8098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516587","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-06","<p>Highways England are not aware of any studies conducted into the financial case for bat bridges. Work in 2015 undertaken by Leeds University, on behalf of the Department for Environment, Food &amp; Rural Affairs (DEFRA), did look at the effectiveness of bat bridges.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England have reviewed the study and met with Natural England and DEFRA to discuss the conclusions of the report.</p><p> </p><p>While the conclusions of the Leeds University work are based on limited sample size, the authors conclude that the effectiveness of crossing structures increases with their size, connectivity and similarity to natural features. They also conclude that wire bat bridges do not provide effective mitigation.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-05-06T08:42:23.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516587/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516587/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516587/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-28","Bats","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what academic studies have been conducted into the financial case for bat bridges over roads, and what assessment they have made of the conclusions of those studies.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL8099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516588","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-10","<p>The carbon emissions from anaerobic digestion (AD) plants have been assessed by adding together; the greenhouse gas emissions from the AD plant including an estimate of their methane leakage rate, the reduction in UK greenhouse gas emissions from the use of biomethane to substitute for natural gas in the gas grid, and where this is relevant, the emissions avoided by no longer needing to dispose of the feedstock. The estimates below are for typical plants and will depend on particular circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>For food waste this net change in greenhouse gas emissions was assessed as a saving of 850 g of carbon dioxide equivalent per kilowatt hour of energy in the biomethane produced (g CO<sub>2eq</sub> /kWh). This arises principally from the reduction in emissions from the landfilling of food waste. Animal waste based AD plant save emissions of 704 g CO<sub>2eq</sub> /kWh as a result of the reduction in storage emissions of slurries and manures. The use of annual energy crops for AD was assessed as saving 102 g CO<sub>2eq</sub> /kWh.</p><p> </p><p>The assumptions behind this assessment are detailed in the Impact Assessment that accompanied the recent consultation ‘The Renewable Heat Incentive: A reformed and refocused scheme’ and did not taken account of any additional carbon emissions impacts relating to indirect land use change, which may arise from changes in agricultural land caused by the expansion of croplands for feedstock production.</p><p> </p><p>This evidence was drawn from the modelling that supported the Impact Assessment for the recent Renewable Heat Incentive consultation that closed on 27th April.</p><p> </p><p>Food waste is estimated to be considerably more cost-effective than agricultural feedstocks because of the ‘upstream’ emissions abatement that is assumed to occur as a result of diverting food waste from landfill to an anaerobic digester. This is despite the controls that are in place at landfill sites to collect and combust landfill gas.</p><p> </p><p>Agricultural wastes are also assumed to produce upstream emission abatement owing largely to avoided emissions from the storage of slurries and manures, although these are less significant than the upstream abatement from food waste. In contrast energy crops do not offer these GHG emission reduction advantages.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-05-10T11:09:27.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516588/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516588/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516588/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-28","Anaerobic Digestion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of how the carbon emissions of waste-fed anaerobic digestion plants compare to those of plants fed by energy crops.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL8100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516589","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-11","<p>It is wrong for good surplus food to go to waste when it could go to people. For food waste which is unavoidable and inedible, anaerobic digestion is the most environmentally beneficial means of dealing with it.</p><p> </p><p>The Waste Framework Directive sets out a priority order for waste treatment: the waste hierarchy. We have departed from the waste hierarchy to place anaerobic digestion above – rather than on a par with – composting and other energy recovery technologies for the treatment of food and garden wastes. We explain this position in our “Guidance on applying the waste hierarchy”. While local authorities are best placed to determine local collection arrangements, they must have regard to this guidance.</p><p> </p><p>The Waste and Resources Action Programme (WRAP) has recently published guidance to local authorities on how to introduce or improve the effectiveness of food waste collection systems. WRAP is also looking at whether greater consistency in how waste is collected has the potential to improve recycling rates.</p><p> </p><p>The “Food Waste Recycling Action Plan”, soon to be published by WRAP, aims to bring together industry and local authorities to increase the supply and quality of household and commercial food waste to the food waste recycling industry.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-05-11T15:52:56.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516589/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516589/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516589/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-28","Food: Waste","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the positive findings of the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs research <i>Digestate and Compost in Agriculture</i>, what action they are taking to increase the volume of food waste going to anaerobic digesters rather than to incinerators.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL8101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516590","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Waste and Resources Action Programme (WRAP) has recently published an updated household food waste collections guide. The guide is aimed at local authorities planning to introduce a new food waste collection scheme. It also provides advice to local authorities who wish to increase participation in their existing schemes. WRAP is also looking at whether greater consistency in how waste is collected has the potential to improve recycling rates.</p><p> </p><p>The “Food Waste Recycling Action Plan”, soon to be published by WRAP, aims to bring together industry and local authorities to increase the supply and quality of household and commercial food waste to the food waste recycling industry.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-05-11T15:58:42.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516590/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516590/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516590/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-28","Food: Waste","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to take further action to encourage local authorities to accelerate the rate at which they require households to separate food waste from domestic rubbish.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL8102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516591","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-12","<p>The Anaerobic Digestion Strategy and Action Plan which was published in 2011 included 56 actions to overcome barriers to anaerobic digestion (AD) using waste feedstocks. The Strategy has been delivered and the number of AD plants that treat waste has increased dramatically. AD is delivering renewable energy into both the heat and power sectors. Government-funded research has shown that smart use of renewable fertilisers can increase yields, maintain soil fertility and reduce bills with no negative impact on crop quality or safety. Government support has helped the AD sector to take off. It is now for industry itself to continue to develop sustainably, identify opportunities for growth and manage risks.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-05-12T10:15:14.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516591/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516591/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516591/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-28","Anaerobic Digestion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what barriers they have identified to the further growth of the waste-fed anaerobic digestion sector.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL8103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516592","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-11","<p>Prison chaplains are already aware that they should not distribute any unacceptable material, including material of a homophobic nature, to prisoners. My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Justice is considering the recommendations of the review of Extremism. As the Secretary of State told the House on 26 April, a summary document will be published in due course. The full report cannot be published due to sensitive security issues.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-05-11T12:31:09.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516592/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516592/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516592/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-28","Prisons: Ministers of Religion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Faulks on 27 April (HL7786), what temporary measures they plan to take, pending the review by the Lord Chancellor of the recommendations arising out of the review of extremism, to ensure that literature of a homophobic nature is not handed out by prison chaplains.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL8104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516593","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-11","<table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2" rowspan="5"><p> </p></td><td colspan="6" rowspan="5"><p>I refer the noble Lord to the written statement of 17 December 2015 (HLWS422). The 94 UK personnel referred to in the written statement are embedded at eight separate coalition headquarters, but I am not able to provide location details as their disclosure would, or would be likely to prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-05-11T15:56:34.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516593/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516593/answer","Hansard__Extract__17_December_2015_HLWS_422[1].docx","Hansard__Extract__17_December_2015_HLWS_422[1].docx","UK Embedded Forces","UK Embedded Forces","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516593/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-28","Armed Forces: Deployment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Lord Ashton of Hyde on 21 April (HL Deb, col 761), whether they will (1) list the location of all Coalition HQs where British forces are embedded, and (2) the number of personnel located at each HQ.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL8105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516594","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-05-05","<p>The UN and UK consider that the status of Western Sahara is undetermined. Since he made his remark, the office of the UN Secretary General has expressed regret at the misunderstanding over the use of this word.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-05-05T13:37:32.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516594/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516594/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516594/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-28","Western Sahara: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the UN Secretary General’s remark during his visit to Algeria from 6 to 7 March that the Western Sahara is "occupied".","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL8106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516595","Attorney General","false","2016-05-10","<p>I meet regularly with Ministerial colleagues, including the Home Secretary, to discuss important issues of common interest, including domestic and international human rights law. I am not able to provide information about any legal content of those discussions because, by longstanding convention, the fact that the Law Officers have advised, or have not advised, and the content of their advice is not disclosed outside government.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","35969","2016-05-10T15:54:47.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516595/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516595/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516595/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-04-28","European Convention on Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, when he last discussed the UK's membership of the European Convention on Human Rights with the Home Secretary.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","35968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516596","Attorney General","false","2016-05-10","<p>I meet regularly with Ministerial colleagues, including the Home Secretary, to discuss important issues of common interest, including domestic and international human rights law. I am not able to provide information about any legal content of those discussions because, by longstanding convention, the fact that the Law Officers have advised, or have not advised, and the content of their advice is not disclosed outside government.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","35968","2016-05-10T15:54:47.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516596/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516596/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516596/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-04-28","European Convention on Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what discussions he has had with the Home Secretary on the UK's membership of the European Convention on Human Rights.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","35969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516597","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-04","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>We are committed to reforming higher and further education so that people are able to choose the next step that is right for them and employers get the skills they need.</p><p> </p><p>Employer-sponsored degrees have benefits for students, employers, institutions and the taxpayer. There are many excellent examples in our universities, which employers and universities may continue to develop alongside degree apprenticeships. Only apprenticeships training will be funded by the levy and it will be for employers to determine exactly how they use their levy funds.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-05-04T14:21:30.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516597/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516597/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516597/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-28","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of the apprenticeship levy on employer sponsored degrees.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","35980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516598","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-04","<p>The Student Loans Company (SLC) administers student loans for each of the UK Government Administrations. Statistics covering English loans to EU domiciled borrowers are published annually by SLC in the Statistical First Release <em>‘Student Loans in England’.</em></p><p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/student-loans-debt-and-repayment/england.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/student-loans-debt-and-repayment/england.aspx</a></p><p> </p><p>At the end of the financial year 2014-15, the overall Higher Education English Income Contingent Repayment (ICR) loan balance outstanding was £64.7 billion. Of this, around 1.5% (£958 million) was held by EU domiciled borrowers.</p><p> </p><p>Between 75% and 80% of the total value of loans from borrowers of all domiciles are expected to be repaid. An estimate for loans to EU domiciled borrowers is not available. Borrowers do not have to repay until they are earning over the relevant repayment threshold. Repayment is income contingent at 9% of any income over the repayment threshold.</p><p> </p><p>SLC has arrangements in place to collect repayments from borrowers who move away from the UK; SLC establishes a 12 month repayment schedule based on the borrower’s income and provides information on the methods of repayment available.</p><p> </p><p>SLC sets up fixed repayment schedules for borrowers who do not remain in contact and will place those borrowers in arrears. Further action, including legal action, can then be taken to secure recovery. European Commission regulations allow the SLC to obtain judgments in UK courts, which can be enforced by courts in other EU countries.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-05-04T16:39:41.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516598/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516598/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516598/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-28","Overseas Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of (a) the outstanding student loan debt held by non-UK EU citizens, (b) the proportion of that debt that will be repaid and (c) the proportion of that debt that is outstanding.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Mr Bernard Jenkin","36023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516599","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-04","<p>The Student Loans Company (SLC) administers student loans for each of the UK Government Administrations. Statistics covering English loans to EU domiciled borrowers are published annually by SLC in the Statistical First Release (SFR) <em>‘Student Loans in England’.</em></p><p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/student-loans-debt-and-repayment/england.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/student-loans-debt-and-repayment/england.aspx</a></p><p> </p><p>Information on the loan balance held by EU domiciled borrowers that are liable for repayment and in arrears at the end of each of the financial years 2012-13, 2013-14 and 2014-15 can be found in table 1 of the SFR.</p><p> </p><p>The information for the financial years prior to this could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-05-04T16:17:16.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516599/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516599/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516599/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-28","Overseas Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the total liability was for student debt acquired by non-UK citizens in each of the last 10 years; and what the outstanding arrears was of such debt in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Mr Bernard Jenkin","36024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516600","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-04","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>I will be meeting with the incoming CEO of the Association of Employment and Learning Providers later this month. My officials have regular discussions with the Association on all aspects of apprenticeships policy.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-05-04T14:33:42.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516600/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516600/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516600/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-28","Institute for Apprenticeships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with the Association of Employment and Learning Providers on the nature of their involvement with and contribution to the Institute of Apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","36078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516601","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-04","<p>The Government published a Green Paper ‘<em>Fulfilling our Potential: Teaching Excellence, Social Mobility and Student Choice’</em> on 6 November 2015. This set out our proposals to drive up the quality of teaching in higher education, and for simplifying the higher education regulatory landscape with a higher education regulator that has the student interest at its core. The consultation closed on 15 January 2016 and we received over 600 responses. In developing both the Green Paper and our response to the consultation, we have consulted extensively across the sector and continue to do so. No decisions have yet been taken and the Government will issue its response in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-05-04T14:27:39.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516601/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516601/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516601/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-28","Higher Education Funding Council for England and Quality Assurance Agency for Higher Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with other government departments on the future roles of HEFCE and the Quality Assurance Agency.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","36079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516602","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-04","<p>The Further and Higher Education Act 1992 enables the Privy Council to bestow degree awarding powers on institutions which provide higher education, and foundation degree awarding powers on institutions within the further education sector. The Privy Council bestows these powers upon the advice of the Secretary of State who, in turn, obtains information and advice from HEFCE and the Quality Assurance Agency. HEFCE’s role in this process is explained in government guidance. Guidance for foundation degrees is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/foundation-degree-awarding-powers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/foundation-degree-awarding-powers</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance for other degrees can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/taught-and-research-degree-awarding-powers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/taught-and-research-degree-awarding-powers</a></p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-05-04T14:11:49.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516602/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516602/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516602/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-28","Higher Education Funding Council for England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether the Further Education Act 1992 gives HEFCE current statutory responsibility for degree standards.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","36080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516603","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-04","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Board of the Institute will be comprised primarily of employers, business leaders and their representatives to ensure that employers continue to drive apprenticeship quality at the highest level. The Institute will also be able to draw on the expertise of education providers, colleges and others in the exercise of its functions.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-05-04T14:25:38.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516603/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516603/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516603/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-28","Institute for Apprenticeships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what role he plans that further education providers and colleges will have in the governance and delivery of the Institute of Apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","36081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516604","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Department has not made estimates of the addition private and social housing needed to provide accommodation for immigrants from EU and non-EU countries.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-05-11T14:56:04.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516604/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516604/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516604/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-28","Social Rented Housing: Immigrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the additional housing needed to provide (a) private and (b) social sector accommodation for immigrants from (i) the EU and (ii) non-EU countries in each year to 2020.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","36094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516605","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-10","<p>The Student Loans Company (SLC) has arrangements in place to collect repayments from borrowers who move away from the UK. SLC establishes a 12 month repayment schedule based on the borrower’s income and provides information on the methods of repayment available.</p><p>SLC sets up fixed repayment schedules for borrowers who do not remain in contact and will place those borrowers in arrears. Further action, including legal action, can then be taken to secure recovery. EC regulations allow the SLC to obtain judgments in UK courts, which can be enforced by courts in other EU countries.</p><p>The Department published a Joint Repayment Strategy in February 2016, which sets out how action will be taken to trace borrowers and act to recover loans where avoidance or evasion is identified. This publication can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/student-loan-repayment-strategy" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/student-loan-repayment-strategy</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-05-10T13:54:27.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516605/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516605/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516605/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-28","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to ensure that nationals of other EU member states who have taken out student loans but do not reside or work in the UK make their loan repayments.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","36095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516606","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-11","<p>The Department published statistics on average household growth in December 2015, including the proportion attributable to net migration. The department has not commissioned research on how immigration affects the demand for social housing.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-05-11T14:56:40.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516606/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516606/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516606/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-28","Housing: Immigrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what research his Department has commissioned on the effect of immigration on the demand for (a) housing and (b) social housing.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","36096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516607","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-04","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>We will evaluate the apprenticeship levy contribution to productivity as part of our wider programme of apprenticeships evaluation. This includes assessing what impact on apprenticeship starts and quality the levy has had, as well as evaluating wage returns of those who have completed apprenticeships. The research paper cited below outlines current evidence on, and the associated methodology used to measure, the economic value of apprenticeships.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/further-education-measuring-the-net-present-value-in-england" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/further-education-measuring-the-net-present-value-in-england</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-05-04T14:22:56.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516607/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516607/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516607/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-28","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what metrics he plans to use to measure the contribution which the apprenticeship levy will make to economic productivity.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","36124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516608","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-04","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeship completions are monitored closely by the Skills Funding Agency. There are minimum levels of performance for individual providers.</p><p> </p><p>We have already taken action to increase the quality of apprenticeships; including introducing a minimum duration and ensuring that all apprenticeships are real jobs. We are continuing to go further by giving employers the opportunity to design rigorous new apprenticeships with end point assessments and by establishing the Institute for Apprenticeships.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to focus on quality as much as on quantity, but do not intend to set a separate target for apprenticeship completion rates.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-05-04T14:19:20.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516608/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516608/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516608/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-28","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will set a target for apprenticeship completion rates by the end of this Parliament.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","36122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516609","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-09","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to my answer give on 25 January UIN 23389</p><p>(<a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=23389" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=23389</a>).</p><p> </p><p>Noting that the first meeting in 2016 took place in March not February and the below additions to the membership of the group:</p><p>Department for International Development</p><p>Surveillance Commissioner</p><p>UK Fire Service</p><p>Police</p><p>Border Force</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-09T10:33:50.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516609/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516609/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-28","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the remit of the Cross-Government Working Group on drones is; when it has met; and who has attended each meeting of that group.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","36083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516610","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-04","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-05-04T16:30:24.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516610/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516610/answer","UKSA Response to 36028.pdf","UKSA Response to 36028.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - EEA Members","UKSA Letter to Member - EEA Members","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516610/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-28","Immigrants: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate the Government has made of the number of migrants from (a) EEA member states and (b) EEA countries projected to migrate to the UK in each year from 2016 to 2030.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","36028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516611","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-05","<p>The Government published details of the cost of the production, distribution and publication of its EU Referendum leaflet and associated website on 6th April 2016. The Government continues to take forward its policy on the full range of European business, including the Referendum, as part of the normal work of Departments. Departments will account for expenditure in the normal way, through Annual Report and Accounts.</p><p> </p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","35594 ; 35595","2016-05-05T13:41:29.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516611/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516611/answer","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516611/answer/previousversion/59173","Biography information for John Penrose","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-28","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 14 April 2016 to Questions 33531 and 33450, what total budget has been set aside by the Government to promote its position on the EU Referendum; how much of that budget has been spent; and how much future spending is planned until 23 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","35992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516612","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-06","<p>The Government will comply fully with the statutory restrictions that will be in place from 27 May. The Government will continue to set out its position that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-05-06T10:55:19.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516612/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516612/answer","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516612/answer/previousversion/59179","Biography information for John Penrose","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-28","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 21 April 2016 to Question 33531 and of 14 April 2016 to Question 33450, what further government activities are planned to promote the Government's position on the EU Referendum prior to 23 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","35994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516613","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>Cabinet Office asked independent polling company TNS to carry out a survey in March (2016). This poll found showed that 85% of the public wanted more information on the EU referendum from the Government. TNS published this poll on their website.</p><p> </p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-05-09T08:44:49.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516613/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516613/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-28","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what polling and research his Department has conducted into public opinion on the EU and the EU referendum since 1 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","35998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516614","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>The Government published details of the cost of the production, distribution and publication of its EU Referendum leaflet and associated website on 6th April 2016. The Government continues to take forward its policy on the full range of European business, including the Referendum, as part of the normal work of Departments. Departments will account for expenditure in the normal way, through Annual Report and Accounts.</p><p> </p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-05-09T08:43:55.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516614/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516614/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-28","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate his Department has made of the cost to the public purse of all activity related to promoting the Government's policy of remaining in the EU, including staff costs and the writing and publishing of documents and web pages by the date of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Mr Bernard Jenkin","36046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516615","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-04","<p>In line with previous answers on this topic, information relating to the proceedings of Cabinet Committees, including when and how often they meet, and which Ministers have attended, is generally not disclosed as to do so could harm the frankness and candour of internal discussion.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-05-04T11:18:19.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516615/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516615/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-28","Cabinet Committees: Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Cabinet's Economic Affairs (Airports) sub-committee has met in 2016.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","36056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516616","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-09","<p>Given the very large and urgent list of other constitutional reforms currently underway, it’s hard to justify giving Lords reform a higher priority than other manifesto promises. We will continue to consider steps that are able to command support from all sides of the House. The Leader of the House of Lords has convened cross-party talks to discuss these issues, and those talks continue.</p><p> </p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-05-09T07:06:15.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516616/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516616/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516616/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-28","House of Lords: Reform","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans he has to bring forward legislative proposals to reform the current method of electing hereditary peers to the House of Lords.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","35972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516617","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-04","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-05-04T16:30:43.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516617/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516617/answer","UKSA response to 35990.pdf","UKSA response to 35990.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - EEA Migrated","UKSA Letter to Member - EEA Migrated","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516617/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-28","Immigrants: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 14 April 2016 to Question 32897, how many nationals of other EEA member states of school age migrated to the UK in each year since 2000; from which countries those people migrated; and what nationality those people were.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","35990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516618","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-04","<p>It is important to ensure that the public continue to have access to factual information throughout the Referendum campaign. The Government has been clear that it will comply fully with the statutory restrictions in place during the 28 day period from 27th May 2016. No new content will be added to the <a href="http://eureferendum.gov.uk/" target="_blank">EUreferendum.gov.uk</a> website during this period.</p><p> </p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-05-04T14:14:34.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516618/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516618/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-28","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 14 April 2016 to Question 33450, for what reason the website eureferendum.gov.uk will still be available to view during the period from 27 May 2016 to the date of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","35991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516619","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-04","<p>The Public Sector Equality Duty requires Departments to pay due regard to equality aspects of decisions. It is up to each Department to decide whether to publish their analysis.</p><p> </p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-05-04T11:17:45.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516619/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516619/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-28","Government Departments: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to his oral evidence to the House of Lords Select Committee on Secondary Legislation Scrutiny on 19 January 2016, Question 7, under what circumstances government departments are permitted not to publish equality analyses which are referred to in government consultation documents.","true","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","35977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516620","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-04","<p>We have reviewed all the responses to the consultation, which have fed into considerations of the detailed design of the new Patent Box rules. We are continuing to engage with stakeholders on relevant aspects of the new rules.</p><p> </p><p>We expect that the government’s response to the consultation will be published later this year</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-04T16:00:00.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516620/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516620/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-28","Patents: Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when the Government expects to publish its response to the consultation on the Patent Box.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","35989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516621","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-10","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) has a Whistleblowing and Raising a concern policy. Since April 2014 concerns raised under this policy have been captured centrally. Prior to this date, details were only held locally.</p><p> </p><p>According to records held centrally by HMRC, for the period 1<sup>st</sup> April 2014 to 31<sup>st</sup> March 2015, 78 cases were logged under the Whistleblowing and Raising a Concern Policy, of which:</p><p> </p><ul><li><p>52 were defined as whistleblowers;</p></li><li><p>20 were defined as wrongdoing (but not whistleblowing);</p></li><li><p>2 were defined as grievance; and</p></li><li><p>4 could not be categorised.</p><p> </p><p>From 1st April 2015 to date, HMRC has received a further 91 cases, of which 18 have been defined as whistleblowers. The 18 cases were categorised as per wrongdoing type, namely:</p><p> </p><p>Payroll and Expenses 3</p><p>Conditions of service 11</p><p>Revenue &amp; Benefits 3</p><p>Assets, IT &amp; Comms 1</p><p> </p></li></ul>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-10T11:35:16.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516621/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516621/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-28","Revenue and Customs: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 26 April 2016 to Question 34460, how many concerns have been captured centrally under the HM Revenue and Customs Whistleblowing and Raising a Concern Policy in the last five years; and how those concerns have been categorised for management of other purposes by his Department.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","35967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516622","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-04","<p>HM Revenue and Custom’s 26,000 (full-time equivalent employees) strong enforcement and compliance workforce of risk and intelligence analysts, compliance officers and fraud investigators tackle the full range of compliance risks ranging from hidden economy to the wealthy.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-04T15:19:48.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516622/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516622/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-28","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 19 April 2016 to Question 33455, how many people are employed to investigate tax evasion in HM Revenue and Customs' (a) affluent unit and (b) high net worth unit.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","36059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516623","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-04","<p>The Needs Enhanced Support Unit handles enquiries from vulnerable customers via telephone calls, face to face appointments and letter. In the last year it dealt with 100,166 telephone enquiries and 22,222 face to face visits to either customer’s homes, commercial venues or Job Centres. In addition it has dealt with 17,252 pieces of post.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-04T12:22:21.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516623/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516623/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-28","Revenue and Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many needs enhanced enquiries HM Revenue and Customs received in the last year.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","36060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516624","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-10","<p>Insurance Premium Tax is a tax on insurance companies and it is up to them how they pass it on to their customers.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-05-10T11:40:37.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516624/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516624/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-28","Motor Vehicles: Insurance Premium Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to exempt drivers between the ages of 17 and 25 who have telematics black box car insurance from insurance premium tax to reduce that tax for those drivers.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","36050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516625","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-04","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) will open regional centres in Newcastle, Manchester, Liverpool, Leeds, Nottingham, Birmingham, Cardiff, Belfast, Bristol, Glasgow, Edinburgh, Stratford and Croydon. In addition there will be four specialist sites, in Telford, Worthing, Dover and at the Scottish Crime Campus in Gartcosh, for work that cannot be done elsewhere as well as a London Headquarters.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC is considering a number of sites at each regional centre location and will give more details when commercial negotiations have finished.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-04T15:16:47.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516625/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516625/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-28","Revenue and Customs: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what current locations and sites have been identified as new offices for HM Revenue and Customs under its building our future plan; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","36061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516626","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-10","<p>Insurance Premium Tax is a tax on insurance companies and it is up to them how they choose to pass it on to their customers.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-05-10T11:39:12.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516626/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516626/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-28","Motor Vehicles: Insurance Premium Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to exempt telematics car insurance policies from insurance premium tax or reduce that tax for those policies.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","36051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516627","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>The new regulations for CASCs were introduced on 1 April 2015. All the changes made were necessary to reinforce the original spirit of the scheme requiring clubs to be open to the whole community, with the promotion of participation in sport as their main purpose.</p><p> </p><p>The Government consulted widely with the sector on all the changes to the scheme. It was aware that there was confusion about the meaning of participation prior to the consultation period for the new regulations. Responses to the consultation were mostly supportive of the 12 times a year rule for participation.</p><p> </p><p>The scheme does not permit clubs to impose fees which are a significant obstacle to membership. The vast majority of CASCs charge less than £520 for annual membership. To make membership more accessible, clubs with higher costs associated with membership are required to make provisions for those who can’t afford to pay more than £520 a year. If no suitable arrangements are made this club is not able to be a CASC because it is not considered to be open to the whole community.</p><p> </p><p>During the development of the new CASC regulations the Government was aware of State aid complaint SA.38208 (2014/NN). At the time, the Government was only asked to provide a response to the complaint. The Government provided this response, explaining why the CASC scheme was not State aid. The Commission’s subsequent ruling confirmed this view.</p><p> </p><p>Since the introduction of the new regulations all CASCs were given a 12-month period of grace to make any necessary changes to remain in the scheme. The Government wrote to all registered CASCs explaining the new regulations and asked clubs to complete a self-assessment checklist on income, membership and participation levels. They were also asked to contact HMRC if they did not meet the new requirements.</p><p> </p><p>From 1 April 2016, 500 clubs have been deregistered as CASCs, affecting some 35 different types of sport.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2010 there has been a steady increase in the numbers of CASCs registered in the scheme. Although the Government does not yet have figures for clubs registered as at 5 April 2016, the breakdown of figures since 2010 is:</p><p> </p><p>5630 – 5 April 2010</p><p>5976 – 5 April 2011</p><p>6165 – 5 April 2012</p><p>6334 – 5 April 2013</p><p>6571 – 5 April 2014</p><p>6715 – 5 April 2015.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","36069 ; 36070 ; 36071 ; 36099 ; 36253","2016-05-11T16:26:24.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516627/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516627/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-28","Community Amateur Sports Clubs Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what communication his Department had with the EU Commission when developing the rules of the revised community amateur sports club scheme (a) in general and (b) on the implications of the Commission's view as expressed in State Aid SA.38208 (2014/NN) that tax relief to member-owned golf clubs does not constitute state aid.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","36068"
