"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516751","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>DWP and HMRC analyse and monitor both the timeliness and accuracy of reported PAYE information. HMRC apply risk based penalties to encourage filing compliance. DWP passes queries about earnings from claimants to an HMRC team who contact employers, software developers and employer’s agents to ascertain the actual position in disputed cases and to educate them on the importance of timely and accurate data.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-04T15:38:21.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516751/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516751/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-28","Universal Credit: PAYE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what measures are in place to prevent employer's (a) late and (b) inaccurate reporting of PAYE through real time information causing errors in the amount of universal credit received by that employer's employees.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","35976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516752","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>The Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, my right hon. Friend the Member for Preseli Pembrokeshire (Mr Crabb) , replied on 28 April 2016.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-04T10:38:44.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516752/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516752/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-28","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he intends to answer the letter from the right hon. Member for Manchester, Gorton dated 22 March 2016 with regard to Mr S Rizvi.","false","Biography information for Sir Gerald Kaufman","Manchester, Gorton","Sir Gerald Kaufman","35975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516753","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-10","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-10T15:50:37.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516753/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516753/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-28","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many requests from his Department for evidence to inform a personal independence payment assessment were (a) made and (b) responded to by GPs and other professionals in each year since the introduction of the personal independence payment; and what the professional discipline was that each of those requests were made to.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","35966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516754","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-09","<p>HM Revenue and Customs currently estimates that the national insurance exemption for people of pensionable age in 2015/16 costs around £950m in National Insurance Contributions receipts.</p><p>This figure is based on employee and self-employed National Insurance Contributions (Classes 1, 2 and 4).</p><p>The estimate is based on the latest available Survey of Personal Incomes (2012-13), which has been projected in line with Budget 2015 economic assumptions from the Office for Budget Responsibility.</p><p>The estimate includes a behavioural adjustment to reflect changes in labour supply for this age group which are subject to particular uncertainty.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-09T14:36:51.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516754/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516754/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-28","Pensioners: National Insurance Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has made an estimate of the amount of revenue that would have been raised in 2015-16 by levying compulsory national insurance contributions on people above state pension age.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","36065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516804","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-05","<p>The Government submitted an initial UK application to the EU Solidarity Fund on Friday 26 February. The Department for Communities and Local Government is in regular discussions with the devolved administrations, local authorities and other government departments including the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, as we work to refine our cost estimates and figures.</p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-05-05T10:30:51.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516804/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516804/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516804/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-28","Floods: European Union Solidarity Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs on the progress of the EU Solidarity Fund application to help people affected by flooding.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","904835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516830","Church Commissioners","false","2016-05-05","<p>The Church Commissioners welcome the Government’s recent announcement of a further £1.5 million for the Near Neighbours programme, which is administered by the Church Urban Fund. This third round of funding for Near Neighbours will help it build on its successful track record of delivering projects up and down the country to transform local areas by strengthening relationships between those of different religious and ethnic backgrounds on issues of shared concern.</p><p>The Near Neighbours programme has offered small grants between £250 and £5,000, providing seed capital for local groups and organisations who are working to bring together neighbours, to develop relationships across diverse faiths and ethnicities in order to improve their communities. The Near Neighbours grants fund has so far awarded seed capital worth £3.66m to over 1,120 projects. These projects have impacted the lives of 941,000 people and 71% of projects have continued to run after the initial seed capital was spent. All Near Neighbours projects are designed to change hearts and minds by bringing together different communities within a neighbourhood so that they can work together on issues of shared concern and common values.</p><p>More information on Near Neighbours can be found on its website at: <a href="https://www.cuf.org.uk/how-we-help/near-neighbours" target="_blank">https://www.cuf.org.uk/how-we-help/near-neighbours</a></p>","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman",,"2016-05-05T13:37:26.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516830/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516830/answer",,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2016-04-28","Community Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, what progress has been made on the Near Neighbours programme.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","904799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516854","Department of Health","false","2016-05-05","<p>The Food Standards Agency (FSA) has responsibility for the Food Hygiene Rating Scheme. Ratings are published on the FSA’s website (and are available via smart phone apps), and there is open access to the data so that others may use it. Food businesses are also given stickers and are encouraged to display these at their premises where consumers can easily see them.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-05-05T07:41:57.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516854/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516854/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-28","Food: Hygiene","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to publicise the hygiene ratings of restaurants and other food outlets in England; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","904828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517160","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-06","<p>Flood Re launched last month, and will ensure people will have access to affordable flood insurance. Flood Re will achieve this by providing reinsurance, with high risk customers having their policies ceded to Flood Re by their insurer. Flood insurance policies ceded to Flood Re have premiums and excesses within set limits based on Council Tax band.</p><p>As of today, 29 insurers are using Flood Re and it remains important that consumers shop around to obtain the best price. A review of the Flood Re scheme will take place in 2019.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-05-06T10:02:04.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517160/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517160/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-28","Floods: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effect of the introduction of Flood Re on people seeking to access affordable flood insurance in areas of high flood risk.","false","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","904826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517163","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-05","<p>60% of our food and drink exports go to the EU; this is worth £11 billion to our economy. This is a vital income for UK farmers and fishermen. If we were to leave the EU, exporters would face crippling tariffs when selling their goods to Europe, such as up to 70% for beef products, which would cost around £240 million per year.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-05-05T15:55:23.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517163/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517163/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517163/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-28","Agriculture: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the potential effect on farmers of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","904834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517268","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-04","<p>The appalling violence that Daesh inflicts is a contributory factor to migration both within and from the Middle East. There are 13.5 million vulnerable and displaced people inside Syria, and over 4.8 million Syrian refugees in neighbouring counties. That is why the UK has pledged over £2.3 billion to Syria and the region, the largest ever UK response to a humanitarian crisis.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-04T15:19:17.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517268/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517268/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517268/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-28","Middle East: Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of ISIL on migration flows in the Middle East.","false","Biography information for Neil Carmichael","Stroud","Neil Carmichael","904859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517269","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-04","<p>Yemen is now one of the worst humanitarian crises in the world. The UK is the fourth largest donor having more than doubled our commitment to £85m in 2015-16. We have so far helped more than 1.3m Yemenis, providing food, medical supplies, water and emergency shelter to those most in need.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-04T15:17:17.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517269/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517269/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517269/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-28","Yemen: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to assist humanitarian relief in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Mr David Jones","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","904855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517270","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-04","<p>DFID is committed to reaching 60 million people with water and sanitation by 2020. We reached 62.9 million people between 2011 and 2015. Improving hygiene is central to our programming. We are the largest bilateral donor for basic water and sanitation in low-income countries.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-05-04T15:27:49.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517270/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517270/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517270/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-28","Developing Countries: Hygiene and Sanitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that the most vulnerable people in developing countries have access to adequate hygiene and sanitation.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","904858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517271","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-04","<p>I have introduced more stringent ministerial sign off controls and this is backed up by thorough monitoring and evaluation processes and management information to better identify underperforming programmes so they can be dealt with.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2016-05-04T14:49:47.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517271/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517271/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/517271/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-28","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what measures she has put in place to improve ministerial oversight of aid programmes.","false","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","904857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516142","Attorney General","false","2016-05-09","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) allocated the following funding to its Proceeds of Crime Unit since 2009.</p><p>2008/09 £ 2,556,535</p><p>2009/10 £ 4,339,422</p><p>2010/11 £ 7,311,688</p><p>2011/12 £ 6,096,729</p><p>2012/13 £ 5,967,226</p><p>2013/14 £ 6,125,024</p><p>2014/15 £ 8,378,651</p><p>2015/16 £10,035,821</p><p> </p><p>The following average full-time equivalent staff in post for Proceeds of Crime Unit since 2009 were:-</p><p>2008/09 41.9</p><p>2009/10 60.0</p><p>2010/11 73.1</p><p>2011/12 65.1</p><p>2012/13 77.3</p><p>2013/14 77.7</p><p>2014/15 124.4</p><p>2015/16 140.4</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-05-09T14:59:37.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516142/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516142/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/516142/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-04-27","Crown Prosecution Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, (a) how much funding he has allocated to and (b) how many full-time equivalent staff were employed by the CPS's Proceeds of Crime Unit in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","35792"
